[4] Israel (Jerusalem)
Date: Tue 6 Nov 2018
Source: The Koz Week [edited]
https://kozweek.com/the-baby-died-from-measles-in-jerusalem-this-is-the-first-time-in-15-years/4379/


In connection with the sudden outbreak of measles in Israel, the local Ministry of Health wants to ban children from school if parents refuse to vaccinate.

The reason is that last week in Jerusalem, an 18-month-old baby died of measles, and this is the 1st reported death from the disease in Israel for 15 years, writes The Times of Israel.

According to doctors of the capital hospital XagÄ§ra Zedek, the baby was not vaccinated against this contagious disease. The girl might have contracted it from his parents, both of whom were diagnosed with measles, and neither of them vaccinated.

The girl's death occurred in the background of the now frequent failures of parents to vaccinate children. The failure of parents to be vaccinated is based on various unproven claims about the dangers of this life-saving practice.

The baby belonged to the ultra-ortogonales, the family of the radical sect Neturei Karta of Jerusalem.

Neturei Karta are radical anti-Zionists who refuse the services of many public services, including health, such as the national program of early vaccination of children.

This year [2018] marks the rise of measles among the Israelites, and the highest is in the ultra-ortogonales community of Jerusalem: 753 reported cases of infection. This is attributed to the failure of the radical traditionalists to vaccinate.

In 2nd place is the ultra-Orthodox community in Safed, with 213 cases registered this year [2018], followed by 89 cases in Petah Tikva and 84 in Tel Aviv.

The Minister of Health, Moshe Bar Siman-Tov, called on parents to "come and get vaccinated. This is the most important thing they can do to protect themselves from this contagious disease."

The Minister said that officials "don't want to talk about sanctions, but if we see danger for the population because of unvaccinated people, we will consider the possibility of a ban on unvaccinated children to attend school."

He stressed that such a move is not for the purpose of punishment but for "the protection of other children in the school."

Bar Siman-Tov noted that the vast majority of ultra-ortogonal families are vaccinated and that pockets of measles outbreaks in Jerusalem and Safed exist only among a small portion of the community.

According to Professor Shai Ashkenazi, Director of the Israeli Pediatric Society, measles "was on the verge of extinction, but due to the decline of vaccination made a big comeback. He urged lawmakers to make vaccination mandatory for all citizens.

